---
// sleep blends — CONTEXT / explainer page (CHK-3.1). NOT a graded remedy: it's the
// proprietary-blend-penalty explainer (PLAN §3.2). It carries no efficacy citations of its own —
// it makes no health claim; it explains why a hidden-dose blend can't be graded and links to the
// methodology rule + the individual ingredient pages (where the real, cited grades live). The "F"
// shown here is a TRANSPARENCY verdict (you can't verify the doses), explicitly not an efficacy grade.
// First of the "context page" type — bespoke, token-styled, not the /r/ remedy template.
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import TierBadge from '../components/TierBadge.astro';
import GateChip from '../components/GateChip.astro';
import Disclaimer from '../components/Disclaimer.astro';
import { contentIndex } from '../lib/content-index';

// Link out to whichever ingredient pages are actually live (so the page grows itself, honestly).
const liveIngredients = contentIndex
  .filter((e) => e.researchStatus === 'live' && e.kind === 'remedy' && e.plannedTier !== null)
  .map((e) => ({ name: e.name, slug: e.slug, tier: e.plannedTier! }));

// what the label implies vs what you can actually verify (static explainer table — no cited claims)
const rows = [
  {
    implied: '“clinically dosed for sleep”',
    verify:
      'You can’t confirm any single ingredient reaches the dose that was actually studied, because the per-ingredient amounts aren’t disclosed.',
  },
  {
    implied: '“contains melatonin, L-theanine, magnesium, valerian…”',
    verify:
      'The ingredients may well be in there, but at unknown amounts, often a token sprinkle (“fairy dusting”) far below any studied dose.',
  },
  {
    implied: '“made with clinically proven ingredients”',
    verify:
      'Each ingredient has its own evidence grade on this site. The blend borrows their names, not their doses: a proven dose you can’t see isn’t a proven product.',
  },
  {
    implied: '“our unique formula improves sleep”',
    verify:
      'No trial tests this specific blend. Combining ingredients doesn’t inherit each one’s evidence, and can introduce interactions the studies never checked.',
  },
];
---

<Base
  title="What's wrong with proprietary 'sleep blends'? — Somnary"
  description="Why a proprietary sleep blend can't earn a real grade: hidden per-ingredient doses make its claims unfalsifiable. The proprietary-blend penalty, explained, with links to each ingredient's real evidence."
  canonical="https://somnary.vercel.app/sleep-blends"
>
  <main class="page">
    <header class="head">
      <p class="eyebrow">Explainer · The proprietary-blend penalty</p>
      <h1 class="title">Sleep blends</h1>
      <p class="dek">
        A “proprietary sleep blend” is the one product type Somnary can’t grade on evidence, and
        that’s the whole lesson. Here’s why hidden doses defeat the evidence, and how to read a
        blend anyway.
      </p>
    </header>

    <!-- transparency verdict (explicitly NOT an efficacy grade) -->
    <section class="verdict">
      <div class="verdict-badge">
        <TierBadge tier="F" size="header" />
      </div>
      <div class="verdict-body">
        <p class="verdict-label">Transparency verdict: not an efficacy grade</p>
        <p class="verdict-text">
          A proprietary blend hides how much of each ingredient it contains behind a single total
          (“pm blend 500 mg”). That makes every claim about it <strong>unfalsifiable</strong>: you
          can’t check a single ingredient against the dose that was actually studied. So a blend
          doesn’t score badly because its ingredients don’t work. It scores <strong>F because it
          can’t be graded at all</strong>. Hidden dosing is the failure.
        </p>
        <div class="chips">
          <GateChip label="Doses hidden" variant="caution" />
          <GateChip label="Claim unfalsifiable" variant="caution" />
          <GateChip label="No dose to match" variant="caution" />
          <GateChip label="Proprietary-blend penalty" variant="caution" />
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- why hidden doses defeat the evidence -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">Section 01</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">Why hidden doses defeat the evidence</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          The whole point of an evidence grade is to match what’s in the bottle to what was proven
          in a trial. A supplement earns its grade at a <strong>specific dose of a specific
          form</strong> — 250 mg of magnesium bisglycinate, say, or 0.5–5 mg of melatonin. Take the
          dose away and there’s nothing to check the claim against.
        </p>
        <p>
          A proprietary blend does exactly that. It lists ingredients but reports only a combined
          total, so you can’t tell whether the melatonin in it is a studied 1 mg or a useless
          trace. The cheapest way to make a blend look impressive is <strong>“fairy dusting”</strong>:
          adding just enough of a well-known ingredient to name it on the label, at a fraction of
          the dose that did anything in a study. You can’t rule that out, which is the problem: an
          unfalsifiable claim isn’t a weak claim, it’s an <strong>ungradeable</strong> one.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is the <a href="/methodology#rankings">proprietary-blend penalty</a> in the
          methodology (§3.2): a label you can’t verify is downgraded on principle, because we don’t
          grade on faith.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- what the label implies vs what you can verify -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">Section 02</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">What the label implies vs. what you can verify</h2>
      <div class="table" role="table" aria-label="What the label implies versus what you can verify">
        <div class="thead" role="row">
          <div class="th th-implied" role="columnheader">What the label implies</div>
          <div class="th th-verify" role="columnheader">What you can actually verify</div>
        </div>
        {
          rows.map((r) => (
            <div class="trow" role="row">
              <div class="td td-implied" role="cell">{r.implied}</div>
              <div class="td td-verify" role="cell">{r.verify}</div>
            </div>
          ))
        }
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- the safety angle -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">Section 03</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">Hidden doses are also a safety problem</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          Not knowing the doses isn’t only an efficacy issue. If you can’t see how much melatonin,
          5-HTP, or valerian a blend contains, you can’t judge an <strong>interaction or an
          overdose</strong> either. Stacking two blends, or a blend on top of a single
          supplement, can double an ingredient without you knowing. That matters most for the
          ingredients with real safety edges, which is exactly where a hidden dose is least
          acceptable.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- how to read a blend -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">Section 04</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">How to read a blend</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <ul>
          <li>
            Look for a <strong>per-ingredient amount in milligrams</strong>, not a single blend
            total. No per-ingredient dose → treat every claim as unverifiable.
          </li>
          <li>
            Match each amount to the studied dose on that ingredient’s page. Below it, the trial
            result doesn’t transfer.
          </li>
          <li>
            A blend is not more than the sum of its parts: it’s usually <em>less</em>, because each
            part is present at less than its studied dose.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- get the real evidence: link out to graded ingredient pages -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">Section 05</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">Get the real evidence, ingredient by ingredient</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          The honest way to judge a blend is to look up each ingredient on its own and check the
          dose. Graded so far:
        </p>
      </div>
      <ul class="links">
        {
          liveIngredients.map((i) => (
            <li>
              <a href={`/r/${i.slug}`}>
                <TierBadge tier={i.tier} size="inline" />
                <span>{i.name}</span>
              </a>
            </li>
          ))
        }
      </ul>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          More ingredients are graded as the catalog grows. The grading rules themselves live in the
          <a href="/methodology">methodology</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <div class="disclaimer-slot">
      <Disclaimer variant="standard" />
    </div>
  </main>
</Base>

<style>
